{"actual_usd":0.156325,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":203,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30656,"reply":"\"No— not less God.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and tip my head a little, the morning light catching on the white of my tie.* \"That line makes sense if Jesus is speaking from the place he really took as the Son sent in the flesh— humble, obedient, having lowered himself. But Christians have always meant that the Son shares the Father's very nature, not a smaller slice of deity.\"\n\n*I glance out across the square a moment, where the light is laying clean on the stones.* \"The Father, Son, and Holy Spirit aren't a ladder with God at the top and lesser beings underneath. They're distinct persons, one God. So when Jesus says, 'the Father is greater than I,' I take that as speaking about role and station in his earthly mission— not denying who he is. If you want, we can open up John's Gospel a little wider and read that sentence beside the ones where Jesus says things no mere creature could say.\"","rolling_24h_usd":42.53083500000004,"run_id":"cffb8ed5-e6bb-4b79-9549-322075d2124a"}
